SIMPLE: litmus
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Litmus
<hw>Lit"mus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D.
<ets>lakmoes</ets>; <ets>lak</ets> lacker + <ets>moes</ets> a thick
preparation of fruit, pap, prob. akin to E. <ets>meat</ets>: cf. G.
<ets>lackmus</ets>. See <er>Lac</er> a resinous substance.]</ety>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A dyestuff extracted from certain lichens
(<spn>Roccella tinctoria</spn>, <spn>Lecanora tartarea</spn>, etc.), as
a blue amorphous mass which consists of a compound of the alkaline
carbonates with certain coloring matters related to orcin and
orcein.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Litmus is used as a dye, and being turned red by acids
and restored to its blue color by alkalies, is a common indicator or
test for acidity and alkalinity.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Litmus paper</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>unsized
paper saturated with blue or red litmus, -- used in testing for acids or
alkalies.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>litmus test</ent>⟦br⟧
